This article is part of my SOLID Principles in Angular series, where I break down each SOLID principle from an Angular engineer’s perspective using practical examples and real-world Angular scenarios.
In this article, we’ll focus on the Single Responsibility Principle (SRP).
Like the other SOLID principles, this one is simple to understand in theory, but applying it consistently in real-world applications requires experience and thoughtful design.
When used correctly, SRP helps us build Angular applications that are easier to maintain, scale, and evolve as business requirements grow. It’s time to break it down and see how it applies to modern Angular development.
What does the Single Responsibility Principle say?
A class should have only one reason to change.
This sounds simple, but it’s one of the most violated principles in frontend applications. Let’s start with a bad example.
class UserService {
getUsers() {}
saveUsersToFile() {}
sendEmail() {}
}At first glance, this may not look terrible, but this class is doing too much. It handles:

• fetching users

• file storage

• email sending
These are completely different responsibilities. Why is this a problem? Because now this class may change for multiple unrelated reasons:

• API changes

• storage implementation changes

• email logic changes
That’s a design smell. A better approach is to separate responsibilities.
class UserService {
getUsers() {}
}class EmailService {
sendEmail() {}
}
class StorageService {
save() {}
}
Now each class has a clear responsibility, and easier to maintain/test.
SRP in Angular
This principle is extremely important in Angular. One of the most common problems in Angular projects is oversized components.
@Component({})
class DashboardComponent {
fetchUsers() {}
validateForm() {}
sendEmail() {}
}As you noticed, this component handles:

• UI rendering

• data fetching

• form validation

• email logic
That is too much responsibility for a component! Components should focus on presentation, and services should focus on business logic.
That simple mindset improves architecture dramatically. A cleaner design looks like this:

• Component → UI logic

• Services → business logic

• Utility functions → reusable helpers
This separation keeps components lean and focused.
That’s it for this article. I hope this gave you a practical understanding of how the Single Responsibility Principle (SRP) applies to real-world Angular development. In the next article, we’ll continue the series by exploring the Open/Closed Principle (OCP) in Angular and see how it influences Angular architecture.
Thanks for reading, and I’ll see you in the next one.
